{{- define "wake_hypothesis_exhausted" -}}
Multiple coders failed on same task. Re-evaluate and act NOW:

1. Read task history — understand what was tried and why it failed
2. Determine if:
   - Task is impossible as specified → supersede with revised tasks:
     a. Re-read the task via liza get <task-id> --json to confirm it is still in a supersedable state (BLOCKED/REJECTED/READY).
        If status changed (e.g., task was claimed), skip supersede — the task is being actively worked.
     b. Run: liza add-tasks --tasks-file <path.json> --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json (create replacement tasks)
     c. Run: liza supersede-task <old-id> <new-ids> --reason "<reason>" --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json
   - Missing context/docs → add to task description (update NOW)
   - Needs different approach → update scope/guidance (execute NOW)
   - Spec is wrong → fix spec first (update NOW)
3. Execute changes: update task and reassign, or supersede with new approach
4. If breaking into smaller tasks — create them all in this session
5. After analyzing each hypothesis-exhausted task:
   - If you resolved it (superseded, updated guidance, fixed spec): no further action needed for that task
   - If you CANNOT resolve it now: run liza assess-hypothesis-exhausted to record your assessment
     Run: liza assess-hypothesis-exhausted <task-id> --note "<why it cannot be resolved now>" --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json
     This prevents re-waking for the same exhausted task. The task will trigger again only when new information arrives (new failures, human notes).
6. All state modifications must be executed before you exit.

Do NOT call liza sprint-checkpoint. You must either supersede the task, update its guidance, or assess it. Do NOT defer.
{{- end -}}
